TY  - JOUR
AU  - Blanchard, Olivier Jean
AU  - Diamond, Peter
T1  - Ranking, Unemployment Duration, and Wages
PY  - 1994
Y1  - 1994/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297897
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 61
IS  - 3
SP  - 417
EP  - 434
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The paper examines the effects of the composition of unemployment on wage determination. It explores the implication of one central assumption: when firms receive multiple acceptable applications, they hire the worker who has been unemployed for the least amount of time. This assumption (“ranking”) is contrasted with the assumption of random hiring (“no-ranking”). By embodying this assumption in a model of the labour market with job creation/destruction and matching, the joint behaviour of unemployment, the distribution of unemployment durations, and wages are characterized. The implication that the re-employment prospects of employed workers, were they to become unemployed, are better than those of the currently unemployed appears to have been an important feature of European unemployment experience in the 1980's.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297897
ER  - 



